Change has been successfully merged
This file has no Harma identifier.

Initially I call it minerva_fanboard.json because fanboards are not part of computing card.

But I think minerva_fanboard.json might causing confusion with CMC's config, so rename it to harma_fanboard.json.
Ack

Why don't we have an EEPROM for the Fan Board?  Or at least some kind of detection mechanism.

In theory you could have a Harma card in a freestanding configuration in a lab where the fan board is not available, right?
We don't have fanboard's EEPROM access from Harma card at moment, and fanboard CPLD has size limitation needs to work on.
We should probably raise this as a hardware design problem.

Lets remove Minerva from the name on all the files.

Minerva is the chassis.  Harma is the board.  There could be a future program where Harma or Minerva are used without each other.
Done
Probably remove Minerva from this?
Done

Do we want this to be a .*?  I'm fine with it being Minerva, since many of the thresholds are going to be dependent on it being used in a Minerva chassis, but also fine if we want to make this a wild-card for consistency in avoiding "minerva" in any of these files.
Done, apply for all configs.

This probe seems unusual.  We should really also be detecting one of the NIC cards, by it's EEPROM, right?

I'm fine with this being added for now since this really seems to be a NIC Mezz, but we should identify it as the NIC Mezz and not the NIC.  Is there not an EEPROM on the Mezz?
I am not sure NIC card's FRU format at moment, I can add probe condition base on NIC's fru contain once we have the information.

I wouldn't really expect a system-specific EM entry for a NIC, but each NIC should be detected as a specific model.  We can get these updated later though.  This is fine to start with.

(I know at least two of the NIC types have different chip models for the temperature sensor)
Should we add a comment to these files to define some of these acronyms?  "PTTV" is unusual to me.

It seems like adding c-style comment into config file is not support, it require source code and python script changes.

I update more information in commit message for now.
EM maintainers: opinions on how to document what "PTTV" means?  Do we add a "Comment" field?
I'm fine with it being in the commit message, though if people wanted an official field for the entity description I'd be OK with that too.

My preference would be to enable json comments, then sort out the things necessary to get valijson working with comments.  That seems a lot easier than just having a comment field and writing code for EM to ignore it, but my preference here isn't very strong.

I've looked at this in the past.  The nlohman change is trivial, the valijson change is probably a couple hours of someones time to figure out.
Hi Ed & Matt, I push another commit for adding C-style comment support, please have a look at https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/entity-manager/+/68065
Name here can be more descriptive instead of the acronym PTTV.
Done, board full name added with comment.
We don't need wildcards at the end of these?  Where do we keep the "EVT", "DVT", etc.?

Hi Patrick, we will add stage at end of board_product_name.
I notice that entity-manager can probe the config without wildcards at begin or end.

For example, I assign "Minerva Harma MB PO" to Harma MB board_product_name and entity-manager still can probe successfully.
```
root@harma:~# busctl get-property xyz.openbmc_project.FruDevice /xyz/openbmc_project/FruDevice/Minerva_Harma_MB_PO xyz.openbmc_project.FruDevice BOARD_PRODUCT_NAME
s "Minerva Harma MB PO"
```
```
root@harma:~# cat /var/configuration/system.json | grep "Harma MB"
        "Name": "Harma MB",
        "Probe": "xyz.openbmc_project.FruDevice({'BOARD_PRODUCT_NAME': 'Harma MB'})",
```
If EM automatically has wildcards, I would suggest at least putting a space after MB.  This prevents future collisions like "MBX" (mainboard expander) from triggering this config.
Done, configurations updated.

Maintainers... how do we get motion on this commit?  There have been multiple +1s given since the beginning of December.  Contributor keeps updating it because of minor hardware changes, but those could have been handled as follow up commits.

I tend to do the +2 and let the author merge, and when I did that in this case instead of it being merged more changes were made. So it could have gone in on 12/22.  I also will wait for you to review it where it's your team.

Since you're happy again now I will +2 and let author merge it.
oh sorry, that's patchset 22, not 12/22.  that was on 12/11.
I think there was an outstanding dependency when you did that +2 (the C-style comment commit).  Thank you.
